ray.rage.scene.generic

Class GenericSceneManager

  • java.lang.Object
    • ray.rage.scene.generic.GenericSceneManager
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Disposable, SceneManager

    final class GenericSceneManager
extends java.lang.Object
implements SceneManager
    Generic SceneManager implementation.

    This implementation does not, and is not, intended to apply space partitioning schemes to the scene, and its cameras, scene-nodes, and other concrete types are, likewise, unaware of any information that might allow them to help at optimizing scene management.

    A generic implementation like this one is meant to perform the most basic operations and optimizations, such as only submitting renderables that are inside the camera's viewing frustum to the rendering-system and handle different levels of detail.

    While it does not yet do such things, improvements to this implementation should remain within those bounds, letting other more specialized packages deal with space partition management schemes, etc.

    Author:
    Raymond L. Rivera

      • createTessellation

        public Tessellation createTessellation(java.lang.String name,
                                       int quality)
        Description copied from interface: SceneManager
        Creates a new tessellation with the specified name.

        A quality level can be provided to specify the amount of vertices to be created for each patch during tessellation. A quality level 5 is the minimum; there is no maximum limit (thought it is recommended to not use values higher than 10).

        The number of primitives is determined by Math.Pow(2, quality), and the call to gl.glDrawArraysInstanced in GL4RenderSystem uses Math.Pow(2, quality) * Math.Pow(2, quality).

        Specified by:
        createTessellation in interface SceneManager
        Parameters:
        name - The name that will identify the new tessellation.
        quality - The degree of vertices to provide to each patch. A value of 6 to 10 is recommended.
        Returns:
        A new tessellation.

      • createSceneNode

        public SceneNode createSceneNode(java.lang.String name)
        Description copied from interface: SceneManager
        Creates a new scene-node without adding it to the scene graph.

        A scene-node is said to be in the scene graph when it can trace its unbroken ancestry all the way up to the root scene-node. The scene-manager is still responsible for tracking and managing the new scene-node. However, the new scene-node will not have a parent; it must be explicitly assigned by the client.

        To add the scene-node to the graph after the fact, invoke Node.attachChild(Node) on the scene-node that should become the parent. For example: 

         parentNode.attachChild(childNode);
        Specified by:
        createSceneNode in interface SceneManager
        Parameters:
        name - The name for the new scene-node.
        Returns:
        A new scene-node that is not part of the graph.

      • notifyRenderScene

        public void notifyRenderScene(Camera cam,
                              Viewport vp)
        Description copied from interface: SceneManager
        Renders the scene from the viewpoint of the specified camera through the specified viewport.

        This method is internally invoked by each camera directly. This method is also responsible for emitting events for any registered render-queue-listeners and scene-manager-listeners.

        WARNING: This method is meant to be used internally by the framework and not by game clients. Use directly only if you really know what you're doing.

        Specified by:
        notifyRenderScene in interface SceneManager
        Parameters:
        cam - The camera using this scene-manager to render the scene from its viewpoint.
        vp - The viewport by which the specified camera is allowed to "look" at the scene.
        See Also:
        SceneManager.renderScene(), Camera.renderScene()
